junit.framework.Test
public class PromptAndRecordTest
extends MediaSessionBase

Test the traditional "prompt and record" feature, available on the JSR 309 Recorder, using options Recorder.PROMPT, and RTCs like MediaGroup.SIGDET_STOPPLAY and Recorder.CANCEL.
Note that the basic recorder features are tested by RecorderTest.

Test Recorder.PROMPT.

A LoopbackMediaGroup provides a Recorder and a SignalDetector that face each other.
The prompt file (argument of PROMPT) contains a modulated DTMF.
When the record operation starts, the prompt is played, and the DTMF triggers the SignalDetector. 

     Recorder           <----->   SignalDetector
  myRecorderWithPrompt              mySigDet
 
               prompt   ------>
               record   <------

test_2_1_9_2_Prompt_BargeIn

public void test_2_1_9_2_Prompt_BargeIn()
                                 throws java.lang.Exception
Test the barge-in feature of the recorder.

"barge-in" means that the caller interrupts the prompt with a DTMF key, indicating that he/she wishes to prematurely end the prompt phase, and start the recording phase right away.
This methods has two steps: first, test with barge-in disabled, and then, test with barge-in enabled.

A LoopbackMediaGroup provides a Recorder facing a Player and a SignalDetector: 

           Player (myPlayer)            <------------>           Recorder     
   SignalDetector (mySigDet)                                (myRecorderWithPrompt)
The recorder is started with a prompt (using Recorder.PROMPT).
The prompt file contains:
"cago-cago-cago-cago-cago-cago-cago-cago-DTMF2"
If barge-in is not enabled, the prompt file will always be played to the end, and the DMTF2 can be caught by a SignalDetector that listens on the other end.
If barge-in is enabled, the prompt is stopped by a DTMF1 sent by the Player, and the SignalDetector remains idle. 
 1) barge-in disabled:
 time
                                                             record() with "prompt"
  0.0s                                          <-- cago ---   <-- prompt
  0.5s                                          <-- cago ---
  1.0s   play("dtmf1")  --->     -- DTMF1 -->   <-- cago ---
  1.5s   play("onesecond") --->  --- cago -->   <-- cago ---
  2.0s                           --- cago -->   <-- cago ---
  2.5s   receiveSignals <--                     <-- cago ---
  3.0s                                          <-- cago ---
  3.5s                                          <-- cago ---
  4.0s SignalDetectorEvent <--                  <-- DTMF2---
           |                                                   --> record
           V
     [[ end of test ]]

 2) barge-in enabled:
 time
                                                             record() with "prompt"
  0.0s                                          <-- cago ---   <-- prompt
  0.5s                                          <-- cago ---
  1.0s   play("dtmf1")  --->     -- DTMF1 -->   <-- cago --- [[ prompt stopped ]]                                         
  1.5s   play("onesecond") --->  --- cago -->                  --> record
  2.0s                           --- cago -->
  2.5s   receiveSignals <--
  3.0s
  3.5s                                       (silence)  --> RecorderEvent
                                                                |
                                                                V
                                                         [[ end of test ]]
Test assumptions:
With barge-in disabled, the test must end by a SignalDetectorEvent with DTMF2.
With barge-in enabled, the test must end by a RecorderEvent.

Throws:
java.lang.Exception

test_2_1_9_3_CANCEL

public void test_2_1_9_3_CANCEL()
                         throws java.lang.Exception
Test the "cancel" feature of the recorder.
The cancel feature is available through Recorder.CANCEL.
This RTC action can be triggered by a DTMF pattern.

A LoopbackMediaGroup provides a Recorder facing a Player: 

           Player            <------------>           Recorder     
         myPlayer                                   (myRecorder)

The recorder is started with { PATTERN[0] = "1" }, and RTC(PATTERN_MATCH[0], CANCEL).
The player then plays a file containing the DTMF 1.
We check that the recorder then stops with the qualifier RTC_TRIGGERED, and the RTCTrigger PATTERN_MATCH[0].

Throws:
java.lang.Exception

Test that a DTMF will not cause cancellation if it does not match the cancel pattern.

test_2_1_9_6_SingleReturnKey

public void test_2_1_9_6_SingleReturnKey()
                                  throws java.lang.Exception
Test the "return key" feature (a record can be stopped by pressing a DTMF).

The return key can be set by a RTC associating a SignalDetector.PATTERN to Recorder.STOP.

This testcase checks that "1" can be set as return key.

A LoopbackMediaGroup provides a Recorder facing a Player: 

           Player            <------------>           Recorder     
         myPlayer                                   (myRecorder)

The recorder is started with { PATTERN[0] = "1" }, and RTC(PATTERN_MATCH[0], STOP).
The player then plays a file containing the DTMF 1.
We check that the recorder then stops with the qualifier RTC_TRIGGERED, and the RTCTrigger PATTERN_MATCH[0].

Throws:
java.lang.Exception

test_2_1_9_11_Cleardigits

public void test_2_1_9_11_Cleardigits()
                               throws java.lang.Exception
Test the "cleardigits" feature.

Cleardigits is set with RTC(Player.PLAY_START, SignalDetector.FLUSH_BUFFER).

Setup: a Player facing a Recorder in a LoopbackMediaGroup. 

   myRecorder  <------>  myPlayer
               <------   DTMF 1
      record(prompt, barge-in, cleardigits)
         [[ wait 3 second ]]
               <------   DTMF 1
      [[ record stops immediately if cleardigits is set ]]
When cleardigits is set, the record does not stop until the timeout.

The testcase is run two times, without and with cleardigits set.

Throws:
java.lang.Exception
